{"/service/ndnp/njr/batch_njr_cinnamon_ver03/data/sn85035720/00279529558/1911010902/0073.xml":{"full_text":"jg^\n1 CLASSIFIED ADS.\nw, .BJ\u2014J ,W,T\u2014\n\"v nini uni i put\u2014' imttmimam\nTen Words y.-yg\u00bbTen Cents\nSTATEN ISLAND NEWS\nOFFICIALS ON\nVISIT HERE\nRailroad Men Make an In*\nspection of System.\n\nGeorge H. Campbell, formerly\nvice-president of the Staten Island\nRapid Transit Railway, now assist\nant to President Williard of the B.\nO. railroad, together with Vice\nPresident C. C. F. Bent, Superinten\ndent P. H. Cassidy; General Traffic\nAgent George J. Brown and Train\nmaster Frederick C. Syze, of the\nRapid Transit, went over the entire\nsystem on the island Saturday.\nThe party, who came down in Su\nperintendent Cassidy\u2019s private car,\nwere at the local depot in Totten\nville about 11 o\u2019clock in the morn\ning. A geenral inspection of the\nentire rolling stock and tracks were\nmade during this trip over the three\ndivisions of the road. It is said that\ngome improvements are contem\nplated by the officials at this end of\nthe line some time in the spring.\nWhat they are could not be learned.\nThis was Mr. Campbell's first visit\nover the system since he was made\nassistant to the president several\nmonths ago.\nELIZABETH DECKER DIES.\nMiss Elizabeth Decker, thirty-two\nyears old, colored, daughter of the\nlate William Decker, of Beach street,\nTottenville, died Saturday after a\nbrief illness of pneumonia. The fun\neral was held from her late resi\ndence at 2 o'clock this afternoon,\nfollowed by a service in Bethel M.\nE. church, of which she was a mem\nber, at 2:30 o\u2019clock. Rev. Wilbert\nWestcott, pastor, assisted by Rev.\n.lames garjeant, of the A. M. E. Zion\nchurch, officiated. Interment follow\ned in Bethel cemetery.\nACTIVE CLUB TO INSTALL.\nThe annual installation of officers\nOf the Active Club, of Huguenot, will\ntake place tonight at its club house\nin Huguenot, avenue, that place. At\n.this time plans for an entertainment\nand dance will probably come up for\ndiscussion. It is expected that a\nlarge fftimher of members will come\nout to the meeting.\nPLEASANT Pl7?NS I,\n\u25a0H.ugupniu, a're^\nJohn Conners has gone to Man\nhattan to reside.\nMiss Lena Mitterway and M:ss\nNettie Polhemus visited in Rerih\nAmboy Saturday.\nJulius Wewner has returned home\nafter several days here with frlendf.\nHenry Bedell was in Perth Am\nboy Saturday.\nMr. and Mrs. Jesse Henman have\nreturned from Peekskill,\nNapoleon Woglom is slowly recov\nfrom recent IILugob.\nReuben Simonson was an out-of\ntown visitor Saturday.\nMiss Ethel Henry has returned to\n^Jiatthattan after a visit here.\nJ, H. Tate was a Perth Amboy\nvisitor Saturday.\nMiss Bertha Walkering visited her\nparents in Tottenville yesterday.\nJames LaForge is having his run\nabout automobile overhauled and\npainted.\nWilliam Bishop is making some\nimprovements to his barn.\nU. S. Grant Council, Jr. O. U. A.\nM., meets tonight\nNo Cause to Doubt\nA Statement of Facts Backed by a\nStrong Guarantee.\nWe guarantee Immediate and pos\nitive relief to all sufferers from con\nstipation. In every case where our\nremedy fails to do this we will sup\nply it free. That\u2019s a frank state\nment of facts, and we want you to\nsubtsantiate them at our risk.\nRexall Orderlies are a gentle, ef\nfective, dependable and safe bowel\nregulator, strengthener and tonic,\nthat are eaten like candy. They\nre-establish nature's functions in a\nquiet, easy way. They do not cause\nany inconvenience, griping or nau\nsea. They are bo pleasant to take,\nand work so easily, that they may\nbe taken by any one at any time.\nThey thoroughly tone up the whole\nsystem to healthy activity. They\nhave a most beneffcial action upon\nthe liver.\nRexall Orderlies are unsurpass\nable and ideal for the use of chil\ndren. old folks and delicate persons.\nWe cannot too highly recommend\nthem to all sufferers from auy form\nof constipation and its attendant\nevils. That\u2019s why we back our\nfaith in them with our promise of\nmoney back if they do not give en\ntire satisfaction. Two sizes: 12\ntablets 10 cents and 36 tablets 25\ncents. Remember you can obtain\nRetail Remedies in Rerth Amboy\nttnly at our store\u2014The Rexall Store.\nBeaman, druggist.\nDoesthis Appeal tcYoo?\nEXPRESS SERVICE AT GO WEST\nFREIGHT RATES.\nYou are a wide-awake, hard-working\nprogressive buslneea man.\nYou know that other things being\naausi 8ii.\u00bb\u00ab>\u00ab be out Gnu.\nIt we were to tell you that our rates\nare the lowest and then were to say\nour service Is the quickest and the\nmost reliable, would not that combine\nUon appeal to you Of course It would.\nInsist that your supply house catch\nour 11:00 A. M. steamer from Pier\nEast River, N. Y. Your freight will\nthen be at ePrth Amboy at 3:30 P. M\nthe same day.\nThe second steamer leaves New York\nat 2:80 P M. and Is due at Perth Ara\nbov j\u00bbr p M\ntnr|r ifew jersey SfoambeaiCo\n4, O. Tice, Agent Perth Amboy.\nHORSE RUNS AWAY\nAND WRECKS WAGON\nA horse belonging to Mrs. O. S.\nManee and attached to a large gro\ncer's delivery wagon became mixed\nup with the large oil tank wagon of\nthe Standard Oil Company, In Amboy\navenue. Pleasant Plains, about 11\no'clock Saturday morning and ran\naway. The horse, which was being\ndriven by Russell Manee, a son of\nthe owner, after It had struck the\noil wagon, broke away from the\ngrocery wagon and ran toward home.\nPeter Schuchard, of Fisher avenue,\nTottenvllle, the driver of the oil\nwagon, who attempted to stop the\nrunaway animal, was thrown to one\nside of the road. The grocery wagon\nwhich became locked In one of the\nwheels of the oil wagon, was almost\nwrecked and the groceries that were\nIn tl were thrown about. The horse\nwas caught at the stable door In\nWoodvail avenue.\nREPUBLICAN\nCLUB BANQUET\nThirty-eighth District Affair\nat Castst's.\nThe annual banquet and Lincoln\ndinner of the Thirty-eighth District\nRepublican Club, of Pleasant Plains,\nwill be held at Castel\u2019s hotel, Grant\nCity, on Lincoln\u2019s birthday, Febru\nary ll. The entertainment commit\ntee of the club, composed of John\nSwade, Albert McGeehan and Wil\nliam H. Porter, is planning to make\nthis affair one of the moBt elaborate\nthis fifth ward organization has held\nin some time. Several well-known\nspeakers prominent in the political\nfield in the city of New York and the\nborough of Richmond, will be se\ncured as after dinner speechmakers.\nAt a meeting of the club in Ami\ncitia hall Friday night, at which\nsome important matters were dis\ncussed, plans for the annual ban\nquet were talked over. After the\nbusiness session a social time was\nheld and refreshments were served.\nMany members were present on this\noccasion.\nMANY AT >TeN\u2019S MEETING.\nThe men\u2019s meeting in the lecture\nMark's M, E. church,\nrlSi&Ti^teteV l^Btcrd ay afternOfll^\nwas largely attended? -%e meeting\nwas in charge of f. H. Grahirft, of\nOrange, N. J., who made an excel\nlent address to those present. He*\nalso sang during the meeting. A se\nries of revival meetings will com\nmence in the church tonight at 7:30\no\u2019clock, and continue every night\nduring the week.\nGordon Brothers, well-known\nevangelists, will assist Rev. Alfred\nEvans, the pastor, during the re\nvival.\nlOTTtwViLLE\nMiss Ruth Albro, of Kreischer\nville, entertained a few friends at\nher home Saturday night.\nMr. and Mrs. William Miller, of\nRocky Hill, N. J., visited her parents\nhere last week.\nJames Woodburn was at the auto\nmobile show Saturday night.\nElmer Juhl has returned after\nsome time In the west'.\nWalter M*Corey has returned to\ntown and has taken a position In the\nPerth Amboy office of the Prudential\nInsurance Company.\nMiss Nellie Dunlgan, of Broadway,\nIs recovering from a recent Illness.\nT. W. Woglom and family have\nmoved Into the house recently pur\nchased from Mrs. Mary Grant, In\nJohnson avenue.\nClarence Jaeobie has recovered\nfrom a recent Illness.\nBentley Lodge No. 670, Odd Fel\nlows, will install Its officers tonight.\nRichmond Temple, Pythian Sis\nters, meets tonight.\nCOREY\u2019S REASON FOR RETIRING\n8ays It Wat About Timo to Give Soma\nOne Elaa a Chance.\nPittsburg, Jan. B.\u2014William E. Corey,\npresident of the United States Steel\ncorporation, who has tendered his res\nIgnatlon, was a guest at the annual\ndinner of the operating officials of the\nCarnegie Steel company held here.\nWhen asked for the reason why he\nhad decided to quit his position as\nhead of the big corporation Mr. Corey\nsaid after a moment\u2019s thought:\n\u201cWell, I thought I had worked long\nenough and thought It about--time to\nretire and give some one else a\nchance.\"\n\u201cWill yon return to Pittsburg, your\nohUuMme, to live now that you have\nmade your fortune?\u2019\u2019 was asked him.\n\u201cNo, I\u2019m afraid not. I like New\nYork,\" said President Corey decisively.\nAsked for a short expression on the\nbusiness outlook, Mr. Corey said.\n\u201cThe business outlook for this year\nseems encouraging, although It is rath\ner too early to make a prediction. 1\nthink the trade will open up fairly\nwell in the spring.\u201d\nRead the NEWS every day.\nBusiness Director!*\nUAistJrET ULEANIKG.\nj. G. Conover, 878 State St,\nCarpet Cleaning and Upholstering\nCarpets made and laid. We aim to give\nsatisfaction___\nGadSfi Brothers. ni HlghSt.\nCarting, Tracking end Man*' Moving.\nOrders by \u2019Phone or Mail promptly\nattended to. Tel. 125-J.\nSTORAGE WAJBESOUSB\nStorage Warehouse Best facilities,\naiean, airy, locked wonts for furniture\nand piano*, *2.00 w\\* Albert Beau.\n134 Smith street B7\u00bb-i-itt\nLIBRARIES IN\nFIREJtOUSES\nLocal Firemen Receive Plan\nat Good One.\nThe announcement that the fire\nhouses of the city of New York are\nto have a library of Its own is being\nwell received by the local firemen\nhere. According to the plan made\nknown a five-foot shelf of books,\nespecially suited to meet the educa\ntional and recreative needs of New\nYork firemen, Is soon to be estab\nlished by the New York Public\nLibrary in each of the city\u2019s fire\nstations of the borough. The plan,\nwhich originated In a branch of the\nPublic Library In Manhattan, was\nsubmitted to Fire Commissioner\nWaldo with the Information that\nmany firemen had applied for tech\nnical treatises on engines and hy\ndraulics as well as for novels deal\ning with thrilling tales of adventure.\nIt was suggested that the Public\nLibrary branches, one of which is in\nAmboy avenue, would be glad to\ntake the lead In establishing circu\nlating libraries In the fire houses if\nthe commissioner would give his con\nsent, which he has.\nPOLICECONIMISSIONER\nDRISCOLL VISITS ISLAND\nFirst Deputy Police Commissioner\nClemment J. Driscoll, of the police\ndepartment of the City of New\nYork, made an official visit to the\nseveral preclnctB on the Island yes\nterday. Commissioner Driscoll was\nit the 99th. precinct station, Totten\nville, in the afternoon, having come\ndown from Manhattan In his automo\nbile. This was the first visit of the\njommissloner to this end of the Isl\nand and he expressed himself with\nbeing much pleased In the manner\nle found everything working here.\nUNION REVIVAL SERVICES.\nThe union revival services under\nthe auspices of the three Protestant\n:hurch of Tottenvlllo will be held In\nBethel M. E. church, In Amboy ave\nnue, this week. Rev. Wilbert West\n:ott, pastor, will preach tonight. All\nire invited.\nCOURT RESUMES.\nThe January terfta ot the supreme\n:ourt, with j\\BfgevLestei W.'Clark,\n>f New Brighton, resumed again this\nmorning alter the adjournment Fri\nday. Several Important cases are\nexpected to come up this week.\nANNUAL PIG ROAST.\nThe seventh annual pig roast at\nCharles Stark\u2019s Raritan Bay hotel,\nat the loot ol Beach street, Rich\nmond Valley, will be held on Sunday,\nJanuary 29. Invitations have been\nsent out for this annual affair, which\nhas always proved to be such a big\nsuccess. A large crowd Is expected.\nMURDER ATHLETE\u2019S MOTHER.\nMrs. fins Kept a Little Store 80 at to\nSend Son to Collage.\nProvidence, R. I., Jan. 9.\u2014The police\nof the state are on the lookout for the\nmurderer of Mrs. Minnie Fine, whose\nmutilated body was found in her little\nstore.\nMrs. Fine was the mother of Louis\nFlue, the Brown university Marathon\nrunner. Her husband died suddenly\nsix months ago, and she had kept the\nlittle store in an effort to give her boys\nan education.\nThe store had been ransacked. The\nclothing of Mrs. Fine was tom to\nshreds In a search for money. It le\nnot believed that the murderer ob\ntained more than $60 In cash.\nLet the NEWS tell your wants.\nSHERIFF\u2019S SALE.\nIN CHANCERY OF NEW JERSEY\u2014\nBetween The Metropolitan Building\nLoan Association, complainant,\nand Frederick A, S. Jensen, et als.,\ndefendants. FI. Fa., for sale of\nmortgaged premises, dated Decem\nber 29, 1910.\nBy virtue of the above stated writ to\nme directed and delivered I will ex\npose to sale at public vendue on\nWEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY EIGHTH,\nNINETEEN HUNDRED AND\nELEVEN.\nat two o'clock In the afternoen of the\nsaid day, at the Sheriffs office In the\nCity of New Brunswick, New Jersey:\nAll that certain lot, tract or parcel\nof land and premises, situate, lying\nand being In the City of Perth Am\nboy. in the County of Middlesex and\nState of New Jersey.\nBeginning \u00ab,t a point In the easterly\nside of First street three hundred and\nfifty feet southerly from Pal arson\nstreet, as laid down on the New Map\nof the Middlesex Land Company,\nthence running In an easterly direction\nand parallel with Paterson street one\nhundred and fifty feet to the centre\nof the block: then southerly parallel\nwith First street aforesaid along the\ncentral line of the block twenty-flve\nfeet: then westerly and parallel with\nPatterson street, one hundred fifty\nfeet to the easterly line of First\nstreet: thence northerly along said\n-line of said street twenty-five feet to\nthe place of beginning Being a part\nof lot 16 in block 39 as laid down on\nsaid map. Being the same premises\nUiat were conveyed to the said Lor\nen t a Broderson by Michael Jensen\nTuft, by deed dated August 29th, 188*,\nand recorded In the Clerk's office of\nMiddlesex county in Book 2*7 of\nDeeds, page 880, etc.\nTogether with all and singular the\ntenements, hereditaments, and appur\ntenances thereunto belonging, and the\nreversions and remainders, rents, is\nsues and profits thereof, and also all\nthe estate, right title and interest of\n,v* said ficfSB&Uiie oi. in, and to the\nsame.\nWILLIAM H. QUACKBNBOSS,\nANTHONG ENGELBREPHT. >_\nSolicitor.\n*25.29._UJ94 1-9, 18. 23, 30, g-\u00ab\nJ. 0. DONEHXHS St BOH.\nOABPBNTEBS AND BtmBKES.\nEstimate* Furnished. Jobbing Prompt\nly Attended to,\nJ\u00abgtt\u00bbs It. A New Brunswick are\n\nEXCHANGE COLUMN.\nWin Kfchange American^ lace rout\ning machine with four dozen bob\nbins, patterns and instruction book\nall complete, value |8.60, for set of\ndishes same as advertised with cou\npons in Evening News. Address T.,\ncare News. l-5-6t\nWill Exchange\u2014X brand new Tvor\nJohnton hammerless revolver, 88 cali\nbre and Brownie Camera with complete\noutfit foT an Edison Phonograph. Ad\ndress Phonograph, eare News. l-7-8t\nEXCHANGE\nCOLUMN\n\u25a0\u25a0i sms. tt .tlX\nNo Answers, No Charge\n.....a\nM W \u2019\u2022-fee\nReplies 2c Each\nr 0\n-a,i\u00bb\nTHE EVENING NEWS will\nreceive advertisements for this\nColumn and make no charge\nunless results are obtained In\nthe form of replies This col\numn is intended exclusively\nfor persons who have articles\nthat they wish to exchange\nfor ether articles. For sale\nadvertisements or other forms\nof classified advertising wlU\nnot be accepted on this basis\nor be placed under this classi\nfication. THE EVENING\nnnwS reserves the right to\naccept or reject advertising\nfor this column.\n\n\u00abi tH t*v\u25a0\nV,\nWhat Do\nYuli\n^0 w\nBOOMS TO LIT._f