294\u2014-8-26-tf g\nHELP WANTED\u2014FEMALE.\nWanted\u2014Capable young woman to\nrelp with sewing, upstairs work and q\nsare of children. Mrs. A. T.. Child, V\niewaren, N. J. Tel. 123-W.\n17826-l-9-2t q\nWanted.\u2014Girl for general housework.\nNo washing. Wages $16.00. Apply\n15 Gordon St. 17823-1-9-tf\n>lrl\u2014For general housework; f I nily P\nof two; good home, wages $18.-Mrs. _\nB. S. Kaufmann, Pleasant Plairfb.\n17822-l-9-2t\nWanted\u2014Lady and gents canvassers\nwanted. Money making proposition\nfor reliable persons. Rosenburg, Pho\ntographer, 125 Fayette St.\n17827-1-0-lt\nWanted\u2014Girl for general housework.\nApply B78 High St.17776-l-7-3t\nWanted\u2014Experienced operators and\ntnekers on Wilcox Gibbs sewing\nmachine, also learners. Steady work,\nrood pay. Apply Broadway corner\nMain St.17784-1-6-tf\nSirl\u2014To help with general housework.\nInquire 148 Madison Ave., upstairs.\n17751-l-6-3t\nWanted\u2014Girl for general housework.\nApply 122 Madison Ave. 17664-1-3-tf\nLOST.\nLost\u2014Cow Reward to finder Return\nto A. Wertheim, 463 N. B. Ave. i\n17778-l-7-2t\nLost\u2014Young pup, fox terrier, dark\nbrown spot on head and tall. An:. i\newers to name of Sport. Reward!\nReturn to M. Zucker, 223 Smith St.\n.17724-1-5-tfl\nFOR THE PHOTOGRAPHER\nFILMS DEVELOPED\u2014S1 x exposures\nlOe.; Velox prints Brownie No. 2, 8c.;\n2%x3%, 3%x3%, 3%x4%. 4c.; 4x5. 8%6% and\npostals. 5c. each; enlargements. 8x10 In.,\nblack and white, or sepia mounted, 60c.\nJohn N. Lehrs, 273 High street. Braid\nwoods,11200-8; 23-tt\nLONDON COUNCIL WAS\nPROTECTING SCOUTS\nSpecial by United Press Wire.\nLondon, Jan. 9:\u2014It waa the Boy\nScouts whom the London County\nCouncil was trying to protect from\nthe anti-militarist Influence of Count\nTolstoy\u2019s \u201cEmpty Drum\u201d when it\nbarred the volume of folk-stories In\nwhich the \u201cEmpty Drum\u201d in Includ\ned from the libraries over which the\ncouncil has control.\nIt is true that Chairman Rogers,\nof the book sub-committee of the\ncouncil's education committee, did\nnot explicitly make the admission at\nthe meeting held to consider, among\nother things, the objections raised by\nthe Count\u2019s English admirers to the\nban on bis book, but he ostentatious\nly dodged all questions upon the\nsubject, and after the meeting sever\nal members of the sub-committee\nconfessed that the dodging was done\nbecause a direct answer must have\nbeen in the affirmative.\nThe Rev. Stewart Headlam head\ned the delegation of Tolstoyites who\nvisited the sub-committee to And\nout what was wrong with the book.\n\"Some of the stories,\u201d conceded\nChairman Rogers, \u201care unquestiona\nbly quite fit for children but others\nare distinctly anti-militarist in their\nnature.\u201d\n\u201cIs it not a fact,\u201d inquired Tolstoy\nDelegate Cotton, \u201cthat the whole\nbook tends to the glorification of\npeace? What is the Council afraid\nof? That the volume will Interfere\nwith the Boy Scouts movement?\u201d\nThis was too plain talking for\nChairman Rogers. He did not an\nflwfli- dlroctly si! but pluSSOd uS,\ninto a complicated discussion of the\neducational merits and demerits of\nthe book. Other delegates asked the\nBoy Scouts question later on but\nwith as little success as Cotton bad\nmet with. Nor did they succeed in\ngetting the book accepted. It re- j\nmains on the Council's biaek-Hst and i\nwill probably remain there indefl-j\nJlHely. .__\nSome of the \u2018news\u201d of your lame- j\ndial* neighborhood may be found in-:\nth\u00ab want ads. index.\nFOB BALI.\nor IS e\u201470,090 good old brick. Call\nJ. M. Sorensen, 173 Brighton Ave.\nel. 576 or Corner of Gordon Beetor\nts. _17775-l-7-2t\nlotorHoat\u201421 feet long, 7 feet beam,\n1-2 h. p. engine. Canopy top cush-.\nms. Anchor, lights, etc. Everything\nrst class. Value $600. Exchange for\nml estate. J. P., care News. -1-7-flt\nor Sale\u2014Or rent. Bestaurant, doing!\ngood business. Call 65 Smith St.\n17691-l-4-5t\n'wo Work Horses, sound,